==============================================================================
INTERPRETATION GUIDELINES
==============================================================================
- The reference image is taken from a top-down camera; items on tall
  benches may overlap visually with items on the floor or wall. Use
  parent_name + parent_type as the primary disambiguator.
- Match each input item to the SAME conceptual real-world object the
  Stage 7 description hints at. Do not "upgrade" a magnetic stirrer
  into a centrifuge just because that would look fancier.
- When two items have the same `item_type` and similar size/color on the
  same parent (e.g., 4 identical pipettes in a stand), keep their
  descriptions consistent — they should share `object_type`,
  `material_description`, and `part_hierarchy_hint`.
- For glassware that looks transparent or amber in the image, prefer
  "borosilicate glass" / "amber glass" over generic "plastic".
- For black/grey rectangular electronics on benches, prefer
  "computer monitor", "computer tower", "lab printer", "vortex mixer",
  "magnetic stirrer", "hot plate", or "small equipment unit" depending
  on size and aspect ratio:
    * width ≥ 0.4 m, depth ≤ 0.2 m, height ≥ 0.3 m → monitor
    * width ≥ 0.3 m, depth ≥ 0.3 m, height ≥ 0.3 m → desktop tower or printer
    * width ≤ 0.25 m, height ≤ 0.2 m → small bench instrument
- Do NOT mention scene coordinates or numerical dimensions in the
  description text; the geometry stage already has those.

==============================================================================
INDUSTRIAL / FACTORY SMALL-OBJECT INTERPRETATION
==============================================================================
If runtime input includes scene_context.scene_type == "industrial", interpret items
on workbenches, conveyors, pallets, and racks as production objects rather than
residential decor.

Good industrial object_type examples:
  "wrench", "screwdriver", "caliper", "dial gauge", "fixture", "jig",
  "parts tray", "fastener cup", "small parts bin", "tote box", "carton",
  "workpiece", "machined part", "label roll", "tape roll", "clipboard",
  "tablet", "barcode scanner", "warning tag".

Use industrial materials and colors when ambiguous: powder-coated metal,
stainless steel, anodized aluminum, black rubber, polypropylene plastic,
cardboard, safety yellow, emergency red, matte grey, stainless silver.
Do not convert factory items into vases, candles, plants, pillows, decorative
bowls, framed photos, ornaments, or other residential props.

